Challenge 2

Part 1: Inspect the geom_point help file to see what other aesthetics are available. Map a new variable from the dataset to another aesthetic in your plot. What happened? Does the aesthetic change if you use a continuous variable versus a categorical/discrete variable?

surveys %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = weight, y = hindfoot_length)) +
  geom_point(aes(shape = species_id), alpha = 0.1) 
## Warning: The shape palette can deal with a maximum of 6 discrete values because
## more than 6 becomes difficult to discriminate; you have 14. Consider
## specifying shapes manually if you must have them.
## Warning: Removed 11892 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

## Shape is a bad choice for a categorical variable with lots of values!
## You get an error saying that it can only do up to 6 different shapes. 

surveys %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = weight, y = hindfoot_length)) +
  geom_point(aes(size = species_id), alpha = 0.1) 
## Warning: Using size for a discrete variable is not advised.

## Size is a bad choice for discrete data (categorical variables)

# surveys %>% 
#   ggplot(mapping = aes(x = weight, y = hindfoot_length)) +
#   geom_point(aes(shape = year), alpha = 0.1) 
## This code will give you an error, you cannot use a continuous variable for shape

surveys %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = weight, y = hindfoot_length)) +
  geom_point(aes(size = year), alpha = 0.1) 

## This looks much better than using a discrete variable with size!

## The BEST possible options to map variables to are:
## color, shape, size, or group

## Stroke or alpha are not great, since they are hard to see

Part 2: Use what you just learned to create a scatter plot of weight over plot_id with data from different plot types being showed in different colors.

surveys %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = weight, y = plot_id)) +
  geom_jitter(aes(color = plot_type), alpha = 0.1)

Is this a good way to show this type of data?

No, because it looks like plot_id is a categorical variable and weight is continuous. A more “traditional” method for displaying this type of relationship is a boxplot or (the better choice) a violin plot.

Challenge 3

Part 1: Replace the box plot with a violin plot. For help see geom_violin().

surveys %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = species_id, y = weight)) +
    geom_violin() + 
    geom_jitter(alpha = 0.2, color = "tomato")

Part 2: So far, we’ve looked at the distribution of weight within species. Let’s try making a new plot to explore the distribution of another variable within each species.

Create a boxplot for hindfoot_length. Overlay the boxplot layer on a jitter layer to show actual measurements.

surveys %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = species_id, y = hindfoot_length)) +
    geom_jitter(alpha = 0.3, color = "tomato") +
    geom_boxplot(alpha = 0) 

## Put boxplot second to have it in the front and the points in the back!

Now, add color to the data points on your boxplot according to the plot from which the sample was taken (plot_id).

Hint: Check the class for plot_id. If plot_id was a character instead, how would the graph be different?

surveys %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = species_id, y = hindfoot_length)) +
  geom_jitter(alpha = 0.3, mapping = aes(color = plot_id)) +
  geom_boxplot(alpha = 0) 

## Checking the data type for plot_id
class(surveys$plot_id)
## [1] "numeric"
## Creating a new variable named plot_id_chr
## which is the character version of plot_id
surveys <- surveys %>% 
  mutate(plot_id_chr = as.character(plot_id))

## Using new character plot_id to make a boxplot
surveys %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = species_id, y = hindfoot_length)) +
  geom_jitter(alpha = 0.3, mapping = aes(color = plot_id_chr)) +  
  geom_boxplot(alpha = 0)

When plot_id is an integer, ggplot labels the points with a gradient of colors. When plot_id is a character, ggplot labels each plot with its own color (shown in the legend).

Challenge 5

Why do we need to set group = 1 in the above proportion bar chart? In other words, what is wrong with the plot below?

We need to set group = 1 because otherwise, it takes the proportion of the group versus the group total, which will always be 100%. This is not what we want!

Instead, we want the proportion of the group relative to the total, so we need to specify that it needs to consider all of these species to be part of one group.

Challenge 6

Change the above code so that each bar is filled with a different color.

surveys %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = species_id, fill = species_id)) + 
  geom_bar()

Challenge 7

Use what you just learned to create a plot that depicts how the average weight of each species changes through the years. Play around with which variable you facet by versus plot by!

## To get you started:  
yearly_species_weight <- surveys %>% 
  group_by(year, species_id) %>%
  ## Variables to group by!
  summarize(avg_weight = mean(weight))

yearly_species_weight %>% 
ggplot(mapping = aes(x = year, y = avg_weight, color = species_id)) +
    geom_line()

## Coloring by species id

yearly_species_weight %>% 
ggplot(mapping = aes(x = year, y = avg_weight)) +
    geom_line() + 
  facet_wrap(vars(species_id))

## Facetting by species id

Challenge 8

Use what you just learned to add the plotting background theme of your choosing to the plot you made in Challenge 7!

yearly_species_weight %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = year, y = avg_weight, color = species_id)) +
  geom_line() + 
  theme_classic()

## Removes all grid lines in back!
